{"questionId":"23330067","questionHtml":"<p>Explain why any integer can be written in the form&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"4k\">\n  <mn>4</mn>\n  <mi>k</mi>\n</math></span> or&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"4k + 1\">\n  <mn>4</mn>\n  <mi>k</mi>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mn>1</mn>\n</math></span> or&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"4k + 2\">\n  <mn>4</mn>\n  <mi>k</mi>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mn>2</mn>\n</math></span> or&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"4k + 3\">\n  <mn>4</mn>\n  <mi>k</mi>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mn>3</mn>\n</math></span>, where <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"k \\in \\mathbb{Z}\">\n  <mi>k</mi>\n  <mo>∈</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>Upon division by 4&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>M1</strong></em></p>\n<p>any integer leaves a remainder of 0, 1, 2 or 3.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>Hence, any integer can be written in the form&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"4k\">\n  <mn>4</mn>\n  <mi>k</mi>\n</math></span> or&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"4k + 1\">\n  <mn>4</mn>\n  <mi>k</mi>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mn>1</mn>\n</math></span> or&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"4k +&nbsp;2\">\n  <mn>4</mn>\n  <mi>k</mi>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mn>2</mn>\n</math></span> or&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"4k +&nbsp;3\">\n  <mn>4</mn>\n  <mi>k</mi>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mn>3</mn>\n</math></span>, where&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"k \\in \\mathbb{Z}\">\n  <mi>k</mi>\n  <mo>∈</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"23330067","referenceCode":"EXM.1.SL.TZ0.1a","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Explain why any integer can be written in the form 4 k or 4 k + 1 or 4 k + 2 or 4 k + 3 , where k ∈ Z .","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"a","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 1—Number and algebra","SL 1.6—Simple proof"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}